              "text": "Allen & Gledhill law firm conference room, Singapore.\n\nAttorney Priya Nair spread out the documents.\n\n\"Hanyang Shipping Singapore SPC Ltd. has been established. Now we need a second layer. An asset securitization SPV.\"\n\nJoon-hyuk asked. \"Why do we need two entities?\"\n\nSu-jin answered.\n\n\"The SPC holds the vessels and borrows PF loans. The SPV issues STO tokens against the freight revenue rights from those vessels. Separating layers means the investor base changes. Institutions prefer bond form; family offices prefer token form. The structure connects those demands.\"\n\nTwo weeks later. Both entities completed registration.\n\nHanyang Shipping Singapore SPC Ltd. — Senior/subordinated PF jurisdiction\nHanyang Marine Income SPV Pte. Ltd. — Freight revenue STO jurisdiction\n\nTax simulation result: Singapore corporate tax 17%, Korea-Singapore tax treaty: dividend withholding tax 0%. Annual tax savings vs. direct Korean borrowing: approximately ₩1.8 billion.\n\nJoon-hyuk asked. \"Su-jin, if father were alive, what would he say looking at this structure?\"\nSu-jin answered quietly. \"He probably would have said he wished he'd lived a little longer.\""
